Prime Minister Theresa May and President Donald Trump held a meeting at St. James's Palace in London to discuss the transatlantic business links between the United States and the United Kingdom. They highlighted the strong economic partnership between the two countries, with trade worth almost $240 billion last year. They expressed their desire to further strengthen this partnership through a bilateral trade agreement and a wider economic partnership for the future. President Trump mentioned the opportunity to greatly enlarge the trading relationship and expressed confidence in reaching a substantial and fair trade deal. The meeting concluded with President Trump congratulating Prime Minister May on her job and inviting her to stick around to finalize the deal.